body:
am i to believe you're ok supressing  -Wno-maybe-uninitialized throughout the codebase ?
I was quite happy seeing stricter compilation enabled on the onnxruntime repo and i would hate to contribute a change to loosen that.
 -Wno-maybe-uninitialized doesnt seem like a warning that should be ignored however it comes from googltest so i'm not sure what the right fix here is.
perhaps the fix is to get this fixed in googletest and migrate to a newer version but i'd let you decide .
 
 the snippet is something i'm locally unblocking myself with and merely meant to provide a indication of what the issue is.
 
 i dont mind pushing the change if you're ok suppressing that throughout .. but i'm hoping you're not :)

~~It depends whether the warning is from googletest's cc files or header files that are used by onnxruntime source files. 
If it is the first case, then you don't need to suppress it. our build pipelines do not treat them as error.
If it is the second case, it is more complicated.  You need do things like https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/include/onnxruntime/core/graph/onnx_protobuf.h~~


It is because googletest always treat warnings as error("-Werror").  The other 3rd-party libraries do not do so. So I didn't suppress any warnings found from any  3rd-party libraries. But this time we will need to do it.
It is cc files and so it appears this one escaped your suppression list?

issue.body:
**Description**: 

In PR #7599, @ankurverma85 found we have some warnings like:

```
~/src/onnxruntime/include/onnxruntime/core/platform/EigenNonBlockingThreadPool.h:1027:21: error: comparison of unsigned expression in ‘>= 0’ is always true [-Werror=type-limits]
 1027 |   assert(ran_on_idx >= 0 && ran_on_idx < num_threads_);
```

**Motivation and Context**

- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Resolve #7583
